5–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1288":"1288","1453":"1453","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Downham, Lancashire, England":"Downham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Downham Hall, Blackley, Lancashire, England":"Blackley, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Downham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Downham in Cambridgeshire, Essex, Norfolk, Suffolk, and Lancashire, and perhaps also from Downham, Northumberland, and <i>Downholme</i>, North Yorkshire, though no evidence has been found for these. The names from Lancashire and Northumberland arise from Old English <i>dūn</i>, dative plural <i>dūnum</i> ‘(at) the hills’, while the others come from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Altered form of English   Dunham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Downum","meanings":["Altered form of   Downham  ."]},{"name":"Dunham","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Dunham (Norfolk, Nottinghamshire, Cheshire). Most are named from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. A place in Lincolnshire now known as Dunholme appears in the Domesday Book as <i>Duneham</i> and this too serves as a source of the surname; here the first element is probably the Old English personal name <i>Dunna</i>. <i>Dunham</i> is often difficult to tell apart from   Downham  .","History: John Dunham (1590–1668) was a Puritan linen weaver who came to Plymouth, MA, via Leiden, the Netherlands, in 1633. He had many prominent descendants."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":43,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":52,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":97,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry De Downham was born in 1285, in Blackley, Lancashire, England. He married Mrs. Henry Dounam in 1307, in Downham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1285–":"1285–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1288–1368":"1288–1368","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1288":"1288","1453":"1453","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Downham, Lancashire, England":"Downham, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Downham Hall, Blackley, Lancashire, England":"Blackley, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1285–":"1285–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1288–1368":"1288–1368","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1288":"1288","1453":"1453","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Downham, Lancashire, England":"Downham, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Downham Hall, Blackley, Lancashire, England":"Blackley, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistyn